---
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import JsonLd from '../components/JsonLd.astro';
import { personKenAshe } from '../data/schema';

const description =
  'Ken Ashe - a marketer and former CPA running a boutique digital marketing firm and building with AI in public from New Jersey.';

const aboutSchema = {
  '@context': 'https://schema.org',
  '@graph': [
    {
      '@type': 'ProfilePage',
      '@id': 'https://kenashe.ai/about/#profile',
      url: 'https://kenashe.ai/about/',
      name: 'About Ken Ashe',
      mainEntity: { '@id': 'https://kenashe.ai/#ken-ashe' },
      about: { '@id': 'https://kenashe.ai/#ken-ashe' },
      isPartOf: { '@id': 'https://kenashe.ai/#website' },
      inLanguage: 'en-US',
    },
    {
      '@type': 'WebSite',
      '@id': 'https://kenashe.ai/#website',
      name: 'KenAshe.ai',
      url: 'https://kenashe.ai/',
      sameAs: ['https://www.linkedin.com/company/kenashe-ai'],
      creator: { '@id': 'https://kenashe.ai/#ken-ashe' },
      publisher: { '@id': 'https://kenashe.ai/#ken-ashe' },
      inLanguage: 'en-US',
    },
    personKenAshe,
  ],
};
---

<BaseLayout title="About" description={description}>
  <JsonLd slot="jsonld" data={aboutSchema} />

  <article class="page">
    <header class="page-header">
      <p class="page-mark" aria-hidden="true">// about</p>
      <h1>About</h1>
    </header>

    <div class="prose">
      <p>
        I'm an AI Optimist running a boutique digital marketing firm. I build with AI in
        public, under my real name, and I write up what I'm learning along the way.
      </p>

      <p>
        I'm not an engineer, and I'm not trying to become one. The bet I'm making is that
        the most useful place to be right now is the application layer: picking up the
        tools that already exist and shipping things that actually work. You don't need to
        train models or wire up infrastructure to make AI do real work. You just need to
        use it.
      </p>

      <p>
        A quick background. I've spent most of my career in project management and before
        that I was a CPA. I run affiliate traffic through various channels, and I'm
        expanding into others with AI doing more of the lift each month. The CPA brain
        helps. I care about evidence and numbers more than vibes, and that's how I
        evaluate every tool and workflow that crosses my desk.
      </p>

      <p>
        So far I've completed three classes: AI Prototyping for Product Managers and How
        to Scale a Business With Agentic Workflows (both on Maven), and the OpenClaw &
        Claude Code program with AI Product Academy. Along the way I've built prototypes
        in Replit and designed multi-agent architectures to replicate end-to-end business
        processes. The tools I'm using day-to-day are Claude Code, Codex, n8n, ElevenLabs,
        Gemini, and Higgsfield. There will be more.
      </p>

      <p>
        This site is one of my projects, built end-to-end with Claude Code (reviewed by
        Codex along the way) as a way to learn the stack in public. It's a sandbox, and I
        treat it like one. Things break here. That's fine. The plan is to take what I
        learn and feed it back into the real client work I do as a marketer.
      </p>

      <p>
        On the "optimist" part: the public conversation about AI is split between people
        overselling it and people catastrophizing it, and almost nobody is occupying the
        calm middle. I'd like to. I think AI is one of the most useful tools we've built
        in a long time, and I'd rather show people what's actually working than argue
        about what might happen.
      </p>

      <p>Based in New Jersey. Building daily.</p>

      <p>
        Ken Ashe is a digital marketer, CPA, PMP, and AI operator building with AI in
        public. He is also the founder of Lucky Domains, a domain acquisition, brokerage,
        and SEO services company.
      </p>
    </div>
  </article>
</BaseLayout>

<style>
  .page {
    max-width: 40rem;
    margin: 0 auto;
    padding: 4rem 1.5rem 0;
  }
  .page-header {
    margin-bottom: 3rem;
  }
  .page-mark {
    font-family: var(--font-mono);
    font-size: 0.8125rem;
    color: var(--accent);
    letter-spacing: 0.12em;
    margin: 0 0 1.5rem;
  }
  .page-header h1 {
    font-family: var(--font-display);
    font-size: clamp(2.5rem, 6vw, 4rem);
    font-weight: 800;
    letter-spacing: -0.035em;
    line-height: 1;
    margin: 0;
    color: var(--fg);
  }
</style>
